<exercise>
<statement><p>
The vector <m>\hk</m> is a normal vector (i.e. is perpendicular) to the plane <m>z=0</m>.
Find another nonzero vector that is normal to <m>z=0</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
You are looking for a vector that is perpendicular to <m>z=0</m> and hence is
parallel to <m>\hk</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
Any vector of the form <m>c\,\hk</m> with <m>c\ne 0</m> and <m>c\ne 1</m> works.
Three possible choices are <m>-\hk</m>, <m>2\,\hk</m>, <m>7.12345\,\hk</m>.
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
We are looking for a vector that is perpendicular to <m>z=0</m> and hence is
parallel to <m>\hk</m>. To be parallel of <m>\hk</m>, the vector has to be of the form <m>c\,\hk</m> for some real number <m>c</m>.  For the vector to be nonzero, we need <m>c\ne 0</m> and for the vector to be different from <m>\hk</m>, we need <m>c\ne 1</m>. So
three possible choices are <m>-\hk</m>, <m>2\,\hk</m>, <m>7.12345\,\hk</m>.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="prob1_4_planeeqn"><title><fromexam>M200 2008A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Find the equation of the plane that contains <m>(1,0,0)</m>,
<m>(0,1,0)</m> and <m>(0,0,1)</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Guess.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>x+y+z=1</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
<em>Solution 1:</em> That's too easy. We just guess.
The plane <m>x+y+z=1</m> contains all three given points.
</p>

<p><em>Solution 2:</em> The plane does not pass through the origin.
(You can see this by just making a quick sketch.) So the plane has an equation
of the form <m>ax+by+cz=1</m>.
<ul>
<li> For <m>(1,0,0)</m> to be on the plane we need that
<me>
a(1) +b(0) +c(0) =1
\implies a=1
</me>
</li>
<li> For <m>(0,1,0)</m> to be on the plane we need that
<me>
a(0) +b(1) +c(0) =1
\implies b=1
</me>
</li>
<li> For <m>(0,0,1)</m> to be on the plane we need that
<me>
a(0) +b(0) +c(1) =1
\implies c=1
</me>
</li>
</ul>
So the plane is <m>x+y+z=1</m>.
</p>

<p><em>Solution 3:</em>
Both the head and the tail of the vector from <m>(1,0,0)</m> to <m>(0,1,0)</m>,
namely <m>\llt -1,1,0\rgt</m>, lie in the plane. Similarly,
both the head and the tail of the vector from <m>(1,0,0)</m> to <m>(0,0,1)</m>,
namely <m>\llt -1,0,1\rgt</m>, lie in the plane. So the vector
<md>
<mrow>
\llt -1,1,0\rgt \times \llt -1,0,1\rgt
=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
           \hi &amp; \hj &amp; \hk
</mrow><mrow>
           -1  &amp;  1  &amp;  0
</mrow><mrow>
           -1  &amp;  0  &amp;  1
  \end{matrix}\right]
=\llt 1 , 1 ,1  \rgt
</mrow>
</md>
is a normal vector for the plane. As <m>(1,0,0)</m> is a point in the plane,
<md>
<mrow>
\llt 1 , 1 ,1 \rgt \cdot \llt x-1\,,\,y-0\,,\, z-0 \rgt = 0\qquad
\text{or}\quad
x+y+z=1
</mrow>
</md>
is an equation for the plane.
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Find the equation of the plane containing the points <m>(1,0,1)</m>,
<m>(1,1,0)</m> and <m>(0,1,1)</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
See Question<nbsp/><xref ref="prob1_4_planeeqn"/> <mdash/> or just have a guess!
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>x+y+z=2</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
<em>Solution 1:</em> That's too easy. We just guess.
The plane <m>x+y+z=2</m> contains all three given points.
</p>

<p><em>Solution 2:</em>
Both the head and the tail of the vector from <m>(1,0,1)</m> to <m>(0,1,1)</m>,
namely <m>\llt 1,-1,0\rgt</m>, lie in the plane. Similarly,
both the head and the tail of the vector from <m>(1,1,0)</m> to <m>(0,1,1)</m>,
namely <m>\llt 1,0,-1\rgt</m>, lie in the plane. So the vector
<md>
<mrow>
\llt 1,-1,0\rgt \times \llt 1,0,-1\rgt
=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
           \hi &amp; \hj &amp; \hk
</mrow><mrow>
           1  &amp;  -1  &amp;  0
</mrow><mrow>
           1  &amp;  0  &amp;  -1
  \end{matrix}\right]
=\llt 1 , 1 ,1  \rgt
</mrow>
</md>
is a normal vector for the plane. As <m>(0,1,1)</m> is a point in the plane,
<md>
<mrow>
\llt 1 , 1 ,1 \rgt \cdot \llt x-0\,,\,y-1\,,\, z-1 \rgt = 0\qquad
\text{or}\quad
x+y+z=2
</mrow>
</md>
is an equation for the plane.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
 What's wrong with the following exercise? <q>Find the equation of the plane
containing <m>(1,2,3)</m>, <m>(2,3,4)</m> and <m>(3,4,5)</m>.</q>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Three points don't always determine a plane <mdash/> why?
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
 All three points <m>(1,2,3),\ (2,3,4)</m> and <m>(3,4,5)</m>
are on the line <m>\vx(t)=(1,2,3)+t(1,1,1)</m>. There are many planes
through that line.
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
The vector from <m>(1,2,3)</m> to <m>(2,3,4)</m>, namely <m>\llt 1,1,1\rgt</m>
is parallel to the vector from <m>(1,2,3)</m> to <m>(3,4,5)</m>, namely
<m>\llt 2,2,2\rgt</m>. So the three given points are collinear. Precisely,
 all three points <m>(1,2,3),\ (2,3,4)</m> and <m>(3,4,5)</m>
are on the line <m>\llt x-1,y-2,z-3\rgt=t\llt 1,1,1\rgt</m>. There are many planes
through that line.
</p></solution>
</exercise>
</exercisegroup>

<exercisegroup><introduction><procedural/></introduction>
<exercise>
<statement><p>
Find the plane containing the given three points.
<ol label="a">
<li>
<m>(1,0,1),\ (2,4,6),\ (1,2,-1)</m>
</li>
<li>
<m>(1,-2,-3),\ (4,-4,4),\ (3,2,-3)</m>
</li>
<li>
<m>(1,-2,-3),\ (5,2,1),\ (-1,-4,-5)</m>
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<ol label="a">
<li><m>9x-y-z=8</m></li>
<li><m>14x-7y-8z=52</m></li>
</ol>
</p>

<p>(c) For any real numbers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>, the plane
<m>ax+by-(a+b)z=4a+b</m> contains the three given points.
</p>

</answer>

<solution><p>
(a) The plane must be parallel to
   <m>\llt 2,4,6\rgt -\llt 1,0,1\rgt =\llt 1,4,5\rgt </m>
 and to <m>\llt 1,2,-1\rgt -\llt 1,0,1\rgt =\llt 0,2,-2\rgt </m>.
So its normal vector must be perpendicular to both <m>\llt 1,4,5\rgt </m>
and <m>\llt 0,2,-2\rgt </m> and hence parallel to
<me>
\llt 1,4,5\rgt \times\llt 0,2,-2\rgt
=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
           \hi &amp; \hj &amp; \hk \\
           1  &amp;  4  &amp;  5 \\
           0  &amp;  2  &amp;  -2
  \end{matrix}\right]
=\llt -18,2,2\rgt
</me>
The plane is <m>9(x-1)-y-(z-1)=0</m> or <m>9x-y-z=8</m>.
</p>

<p>We can check this by observing that
<m>(1,0,1),\ (2,4,6)</m> and <m>(1,2,-1)</m> all satisfy <m>9x-y-z=8</m>.
</p>

<p>(b) The plane must be parallel to
<m>\llt 4,-4,4\rgt -\llt 1,-2,-3\rgt =\llt 3,-2,7\rgt </m>
and to <m>\llt 3,2,-3\rgt -\llt 1,-2,-3\rgt =\llt 2,4,0\rgt </m>. So its normal
vector must be perpendicular to both <m>\llt 3,-2,7\rgt </m> and <m>\llt 2,4,0\rgt</m>
and hence parallel to
<me>
\llt 3,-2,7\rgt \times\llt 2,4,0\rgt
=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
           \hi &amp; \hj &amp; \hk \\
           3  &amp;  -2  &amp;  7 \\
           2  &amp;  4  &amp;  0
  \end{matrix}\right]
=\llt -28,14,16\rgt
</me>
The plane is <m>14(x-1)-7(y+2)-8(z+3)=0</m> or <m>14x-7y-8z=52</m>.
</p>

<p>We can check this by observing that
<m>(1,-2,-3),\ (4,-4,4)</m> and <m>(3,2,-3)</m> all satisfy <m>14x-7y-8z=52</m>.
</p>

<p>(c) The plane must be parallel to
     <m>\llt 5,2,1\rgt -\llt 1,-2,-3\rgt =\llt 4,4,4\rgt </m>
 and to <m>\llt -1,-4,-5\rgt -\llt 1,-2,-3\rgt =\llt -2,-2,-2\rgt </m>.
My, my. These two vectors are parallel. So the three points are all on the
same straight line. Any plane containing the line contains all three points.
If <m>\llt a,b,c\rgt</m> is any vector perpendicular to <m>\llt 1,1,1\rgt</m>
(i.e. which obeys <m>a+b+c=0</m>) then the plane
<m>a(x-1)+b(y+2)+c(z+3)=0</m> or <m>a(x-1)+b(y+2)-(a+b)(z+3)=0</m>
or <m>ax+by-(a+b)z=4a+b</m> contains the three given points.
</p>

<p>We can check this by observing that
<m>(1,-2,-3),\ (5,2,1)</m> and <m>(-1,-4,-5)</m> all
satisfy the equation <m>ax+by-(a+b)z=4a+b</m> for all <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Find the distance from the given point to the given plane.
<ol label="a">
<li>
point <m>(-1,2,3)</m>, plane <m>x+y+z=7</m>
</li>
<li>
point <m>(1,-4,3)</m>, plane <m>x-2y+z=5</m>
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<ol label="a">
<li><m>\sqrt{3}</m></li>
<li><m>7/\sqrt{6}</m></li>
</ol>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
(a) One point on the plane is <m>(0,0,7)</m>. The vector from <m>(-1,2,3)</m>
to <m>(0,0,7)</m> is <m>\llt 0,0,7\rgt -\llt -1,2,3\rgt =\llt 1,-2,4\rgt </m>.
A unit vector perpendicular to the plane is
<m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\llt 1,1,1\rgt </m>. The distance from
<m>(-1,2,3)</m> to the plane is the length of the projection of
<m>\llt 1,-2,4\rgt </m> on <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\llt 1,1,1\rgt </m> which is <md>
<mrow>
\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\llt 1,1,1\rgt \cdot\llt 1,-2,4\rgt
=\frac{3}{\sqrt{3}}
=\sqrt{3}
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>(b) One point on the plane is <m>(0,0,5)</m>. The vector from
<m>(1,-4,3)</m> to <m>(0,0,5)</m> is <m>\llt 0,0,5\rgt -\llt 1,-4,3\rgt =\llt -1,4,2\rgt</m>. A unit vector perpendicular to the plane is
<m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}\llt 1,-2,1\rgt </m>. The distance from
<m>(1,-4,3)</m> to the plane is the length of the projection of
<m>\llt -1,4,2\rgt </m> on <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}\llt 1,-2,1\rgt </m> which is
the absolute value of
<me>
\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}\llt 1,-2,1\rgt \cdot \llt -1,4,2\rgt
=\frac{-7}{\sqrt{6}}
</me>
or <m>7/\sqrt{6}</m>.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M200 2007A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
A plane <m>\Pi</m> passes through the points <m>A = (1, 1, 3)</m>, <m>B = (2, 0, 2)</m>
and <m>C = (2, 1, 0)</m> in <m>\bbbr^3</m>.
<ol label="a">
<li>
 Find an equation for the plane <m>\Pi</m>.
</li>
<li>
 Find the point <m>E</m> in the plane <m>\Pi</m> such that the line <m>L</m> through
<m>D = (6, 1, 2)</m> and <m>E</m> is perpendicular to <m>\Pi</m>.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<ol label="a">
<li><m>3x+2y+z = 8</m></li>
<li><m>\big(3\,,\,-1\,,\,1\big)</m></li>
</ol>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
(a)
The vector from <m>C</m> to <m>A</m>, namely
 <m>\llt 1-2\,,\,1-1\,,\,3-0\rgt = \llt -1\,,\,0\,,\,3\rgt</m> lies entirely inside
<m>\Pi</m>.
The vector from <m>C</m> to <m>B</m>, namely
 <m>\llt 2-2\,,\,0-1\,,\,2-0\rgt = \llt 0\,,\,-1\,,\,2\rgt</m> also
lies entirely inside  <m>\Pi</m>.  Consequently, the vector
<md>
<mrow>
\llt -1\,,\,0\,,\,3\rgt\times \llt 0\,,\,-1\,,\,2\rgt
=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
            \hi  &amp;  \hj  &amp;  \hk
</mrow><mrow>
            -1    &amp;  0   &amp;    3
</mrow><mrow>
            0    &amp;   -1   &amp;    2
            \end{matrix}\right]
=\llt 3 \,,\, 2 \,,\, 1 \rgt
</mrow>
</md>
is perpendicular to <m>\Pi</m>. The equation of <m>\Pi</m> is then
<md>
<mrow>
\llt 3 \,,\, 2 \,,\, 1 \rgt \cdot \llt x-2 \,,\, y-1 \,,\, z \rgt = 0
\qquad\text{or}\qquad
3x+2y+z = 8
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>(b) Let <m>E</m> be <m>(x,y,z)</m>. Then the vector from <m>D</m> to <m>E</m>,
namely <m>\llt x-6\,,\,y-1\,,\,z-2\rgt</m> has to be parallel to
the vector <m>\llt 3 \,,\, 2 \,,\, 1 \rgt</m>, which is perpendicular to
<m>\Pi</m>. That is, there must be a number <m>t</m> such that
<md>
<mrow>
&amp; \llt x-6\,,\,y-1\,,\,z-2\rgt = t \llt 3 \,,\, 2 \,,\, 1 \rgt
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\text{or }x=6+3t,\ y=1+2t,\ z=2+t
</mrow>
</md>
As <m>(x,y,z)</m> must be in <m>\Pi</m>,
<md>
<mrow>
8 = 3x+2y+z = 3(6+3t) + 2(1+2t) +(2+t) = 22 +14 t
\implies t=-1
</mrow>
</md>
So <m>(x,y,z) = \big(6+3(-1)\,,\,1+2(-1)\,,\,2+(-1)\big)
            = \big(3\,,\,-1\,,\,1\big)</m>.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M200 2011A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let <m>A = (2, 3, 4)</m> and let <m>L</m> be the line given by the equations <m>x + y = 1</m> and
<m>x + 2y + z = 3</m>.
<ol label="a">
<li>
Write an equation for the plane containing <m>A</m> and perpendicular to <m>L</m>.
</li>
<li>
Write an equation for the plane containing <m>A</m> and <m>L</m>.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<ol label="a">
<li><m>x-y+z=3</m></li>
<li><m>5x+y-4z=-3</m></li>
</ol>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
We are going to need a direction vector for <m>L</m> in both parts (a) and (b).
So we find one first.
<ul>
<li>
The vector <m>\llt 1,1,0\rgt</m> is perpendicular to <m>x + y = 1</m>
and hence to <m>L</m>.
</li>
<li>
The vector <m>\llt 1,2,1\rgt</m> is perpendicular to <m>x + 2y + z = 3</m>
and hence to <m>L</m>.
</li>
</ul>
So the vector
<md>
<mrow>
\llt 1,1,0\rgt \times \llt 1,2,1\rgt
    =\det\left[\begin{matrix}
            \hi  &amp;  \hj  &amp;  \hk
</mrow><mrow>
            1    &amp;   1   &amp;   0
</mrow><mrow>
            1    &amp;   2   &amp;    1
            \end{matrix}\right]
=\llt 1 \,,\, -1 \,,\, 1 \rgt
</mrow>
</md>
is a direction vector for <m>L</m>.
</p>

<p>(a) The plane is to contain the point <m>(2,3,4)</m> and is to have
<m>\llt-1,1,-1 \rgt</m> as a normal vector. So
<md>
<mrow>
\llt-1,1,-1 \rgt\cdot \llt x-2,y-3,z-4 \rgt =0\qquad\text{or}\qquad
x-y+z=3
</mrow>
</md>
does the job.
</p>

<p>(b) The plane is to contain the points <m>A=(2,3,4)</m> and <m>(1,0,2)</m>
(which is on <m>L</m>) so that the vector <m> \llt 2-1,3-0,4-2 \rgt
=\llt 1,3,2 \rgt</m> is to be parallel to the plane. The direction
vector of <m>L</m>, namely <m>\llt -1 , 1 , -1 \rgt</m>, is also to be parallel
to the plane. So the vector
<md>
<mrow>
\llt 1,3,2\rgt \times \llt -1,1,-1\rgt
    =\det\left[\begin{matrix}
            \hi  &amp;  \hj  &amp;  \hk
</mrow><mrow>
            1    &amp;   3   &amp;   2
</mrow><mrow>
            -1   &amp;   1   &amp;  -1
            \end{matrix}\right]
=\llt -5 \,,\, -1 \,,\, 4 \rgt
</mrow>
</md>
is to be normal to the plane. So
<md>
<mrow>
\llt-5,-1,4 \rgt\cdot \llt x-2,y-3,z-4 \rgt =0\qquad\text{or}\qquad
5x+y-4z=-3
</mrow>
</md>
does the job.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M200 2015D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Consider the plane <m>4x + 2y - 4z = 3</m>. Find all parallel planes that
are distance <m>2</m> from the above plane. Your answers should be in the
following form: <m>4x + 2y - 4z = C</m>.
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<m>4x + 2y - 4z=15</m> and <m>4x + 2y - 4z=-9</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
All planes that are parallel to the plane <m>4x + 2y - 4z = 3</m>
must have <m>\llt 4\,,\,2\,,\,-4\rgt</m> as a normal vector and
hence must have an equation of the form <m>4x + 2y - 4z = C</m>
for some constant <m>C</m>. We must find the <m>C</m>'s for which the distance
from  <m>4x + 2y - 4z = 3</m> to <m>4x + 2y - 4z = C</m> is <m>2</m>.
One point on <m>4x + 2y - 4z = 3</m> is <m>\big(0,\frac{3}{2},0\big)</m>.
The two points <m>(x',y',z')</m> with
<md>
<mrow>
\overbrace{\llt x'-0\,,\,y'-\frac{3}{2}\,,\,z'-0\rgt}^{\text{vector from}
\big(0,\frac{3}{2},0\big)\text{ to } (x',y',z')}
=\pm 2\ \overbrace{\frac{\llt 4\,,\,2\,,\,-4\rgt}{\sqrt{16+4+16}}}^{\text{unit vector}}
=\pm \frac{2}{6} \llt 4\,,\,2\,,\,-4\rgt
=\pm\llt \frac{4}{3}\,,\,\frac{2}{3}\,,\,-\frac{4}{3}\rgt
</mrow>
</md>
are the two points that are a distance <m>2</m> from <m>\big(0,\frac{3}{2},0\big)</m>
in the direction of the normal.The two points <m>(x',y',z')</m> are
<md>
<mrow>
\left(0+\frac{4}{3}\,,\, \frac{3}{2}+\frac{2}{3}\,,\,0-\frac{4}{3}\right)
&amp;=\left(\frac{4}{3}\,,\, \frac{13}{6}\,,\,-\frac{4}{3}\right)
</mrow><mrow>\text{ and }
\left(0-\frac{4}{3}\,,\, \frac{3}{2}-\frac{2}{3}\,,\,0+\frac{4}{3}\right)
&amp;=\left(-\frac{4}{3}\,,\, \frac{5}{6}\,,\,\frac{4}{3}\right)
</mrow>
</md>
These two points lie on the desired planes, so the two desired planes are
<md>
<mrow>
4x + 2y - 4z
=\frac{4\times 4}{3} +\frac{2\times 13}{6}-\frac{-4\times 4}{3}
=\frac{32+26+32}{6}
=15
</mrow>
</md>
and
<md>
<mrow>
4x + 2y - 4z
=\frac{4\times(-4)}{3} +\frac{2\times 5}{6}-\frac{4\times 4}{3}
=\frac{-32+10-32}{6}
=-9
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M200 2004A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Find the distance from the point <m>(1,2,3)</m> to the plane that passes through
the points <m>(0,1,1)</m>, <m>(1,-1,3)</m> and <m>(2,0,-1)</m>.
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<m>2</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
The two vectors
<md alignment="alignat">
<mrow>{3}
\va&amp;=\llt 1,-1,3\rgt - \llt 0,1,1\rgt &amp;&amp;= \llt 1,-2, 2\rgt
</mrow><mrow>
\vb&amp;=\llt 2,0,-1\rgt - \llt 0,1,1\rgt &amp;&amp;= \llt 2,-1,-2\rgt
</mrow>
</md>
both lie entirely inside the plane. So the vector
<me>
\va\times\vb
   =\det\left[\begin{matrix}
           \hi &amp; \hj &amp; \hk \\
            1  &amp;  -2  &amp;  2 \\
            2  &amp;  -1 &amp;  -2
  \end{matrix}\right]
   =\llt 6,6,3\rgt
</me>
is perpendicular to the plane. The vector
     <m>\vc=\frac{1}{3}\llt 6,6,3\rgt =\llt 2,2,1\rgt</m>
is also perpendicular to the plane. The vector
<me>
\vd=\llt 1,2,3\rgt-\llt 0,1,1\rgt=\llt 1,1,2\rgt
</me>
joins the point to the plane. So, if <m>\theta</m> is the angle between <m>\vd</m> and
<m>\vc</m>, the distance is
<me>
|\vd|\cos\theta=\frac{\vc\cdot\vd}{|\vc|}=\frac{6}{\sqrt{9}}=2
</me>
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>
</exercisegroup>

<exercisegroup><introduction><application/></introduction>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M200 2014A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Consider two planes <m>W_1</m>, <m>W_2</m>, and a line <m>M</m> defined by:
<me>
W_1\ :\  -2x + y + z = 7,\qquad
W_2\ :\ -x + 3y + 3z = 6,\qquad
M\ :\
\frac{x}{2} = \frac{2y-4}{4} = z + 5.
</me>
<ol label="a">
<li>
Find a parametric equation of the line of intersection <m>L</m> of <m>W_1</m> and <m>W_2</m>.
</li>
<li>
Find the distance from L to M .
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<ol label="a">
<li><m>(x,y,z) = (-3,1,0) +t \llt 0,-1,1\rgt</m></li>
<li><m>\sqrt{17}</m></li>
</ol>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
(a) Let's use <m>z</m> as the parameter and rename it to <m>t</m>.
That is, <m>z=t</m>. Subtracting <m>2</m> times the <m>W_2</m> equation from the <m>W_1</m>
equation gives
<me>
-5y -5z = -5
\implies y = 1-z = 1-t\quad\text{ or }\quad y-1=-t
</me>
Substituting the result into the equation for <m>W_2</m> gives
<md>
<mrow>
-x +3(1-t) +3t =6
\implies x = -3\quad\text{ or }\quad x+3=0
</mrow>
</md>
So a parametric equation is
<me>
\llt x+3,y-1,z\rgt = t \llt 0,-1,1\rgt
</me>
</p>

<p>(b) <em>Solution 1</em>
</p>

<p>We can also parametrize <m>M</m> using <m>z=t</m>:
<me>
x=2z+10=2t+10,\
y=2z+12=2t+12\quad\implies\quad
\llt x,y,z\rgt = \llt 10,12,0\rgt +t \llt 2,2,1\rgt
</me>
So one point on <m>M</m> is <m>(10,12,0)</m> and one point on <m>L</m> is <m>(-3,1,0)</m> and
<me>
\vv= \llt (-3)-10\,,\, 1 -12  \,,\,  0-0\rgt
   =\llt  -13 \,,\, -11  \,,\, 0\rgt
</me>
is one vector from a point on <m>M</m> to a point on <m>L</m>.
</p>

<p>The direction vectors of <m>L</m> and <m>M</m> are <m>\llt 0,-1,1\rgt</m> and
<m>\llt 2,2,1\rgt</m>, respectively. The vector
<md>
<mrow>
\vn = \llt 0,-1,1\rgt \times \llt 2,2,1\rgt
=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
            \hi  &amp;  \hj  &amp;  \hk
</mrow><mrow>
            0    &amp;  -1   &amp;    1
</mrow><mrow>
            2    &amp;   2   &amp;    1
            \end{matrix}\right]
=\llt -3 \,,\, 2 \,,\, 2 \rgt
</mrow>
</md>
is then perpendicular to both <m>L</m> and <m>M</m>.
</p>

<p>The distance from <m>L</m> to <m>M</m> is then the length of the projection
of <m>\vv</m> on <m>\vn</m>, which is
<md>
<mrow>
\frac{|\vv\cdot\vn|}{|\vn|}
=\frac{|39-22+0|}{\sqrt{9+4+4}}
=\sqrt{17}
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>(b) <em>Solution 2</em>
We can also parametrize <m>M</m> using <m>z=s</m>:
<me>
x=2z+10=2s+10,\
y=2z+12=2s+12\quad\implies\quad
\llt x,y,z\rgt = \llt 10,12,0\rgt +s \llt 2,2,1\rgt
</me>
The vector from the point  <m>(-3\,,\,1-t\,,\,t)</m> on <m>L</m>
to the point <m>(10+2s\,,\,12+2s\,,\,s)</m> on <m>M</m> is
<me>
\llt 13+2s \,,\, 11+2s+t \,,\, s-t \rgt
</me>
So the distance from the point  <m>(-3\,,\,1-t\,,\,t)</m> on <m>L</m>
to the point <m>(10+2s\,,\,12+2s\,,\,s)</m> on <m>M</m> is the square root of
<me>
D(s,t) = (13+2s)^2 +(11+2s+t)^2 +(s-t)^2
</me>
That distance is minimized when
<md>
<mrow>
0 = \pdiff{D}{s} &amp;=4(13+2s) +4(11+2s+t) +2(s-t)
</mrow><mrow>
0 = \pdiff{D}{t} &amp;=2(11+2s+t) -2(s-t)
</mrow>
</md>
Cleaning up those equations gives
<md>
<mrow>
18s +2t &amp;= -96
</mrow><mrow>
2s  +4t &amp;=-22
</mrow>
</md>
or
<md>
<mrow>
9s +t &amp;=-48 \tag{E1}
</mrow><mrow>
 s+2t &amp;=-11 \tag{E2}
</mrow>
</md>
Subtracting (E2) from twice (E1) gives
<me>
17s = -85 \implies s=-5
</me>
Substituting that into (E2) gives
<me>
2t= -11 +5 \implies t = -3
</me>
Note that
<md>
<mrow>
13+2s &amp;= 3
</mrow><mrow>
11+2s+t &amp;= -2
</mrow><mrow>
s-t &amp;= -2
</mrow>
</md>
So the distance is
<md>
<mrow>
\sqrt{D(-5,-3)}
&amp;=\sqrt{3^2 + (-2)^2 + (-2)^2}
=\sqrt{17}
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Find the equation of the sphere which has the two planes
<m>x+y+z=3,\ x+y+z=9</m> as tangent planes if the center of the sphere is on
the planes <m>2x-y=0,\ 3x-z=0</m>.
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<m>(x-1)^2+(y-2)^2+(z-3)^2=3</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
The two planes <m>x+y+z=3</m> and <m>x+y+z=9</m> are parallel.
The centre must be on the plane <m>x+y+z=6</m> half way between them.
So, the center is on <m>x+y+z=6</m>, <m>2x-y=0</m> and <m>3x-z=0</m>. Solving these
three equations, or equvalently,
<me>
y=2x,\ z=3x,\ x+y+z=6x=6
</me>
gives <m>(1,2,3)</m> as the centre. <m>(1,1,1)</m> is a point on
<m>x+y+z=3</m>. <m>(3,3,3)</m> is a point on <m>x+y+z=9</m>. So <m>\llt 2,2,2\rgt</m> is a vector
with tail on <m>x+y+x=3</m> and head on <m>x+y+z=9</m>. Furthermore <m>\llt 2,2,2\rgt</m>
is perpendicular to the two planes. So the distance between the planes
is <m>|\llt 2,2,2\rgt|=2\sqrt{3}</m> and the radius of the sphere is <m>\sqrt{3}</m>.
The sphere is
<me>
(x-1)^2+(y-2)^2+(z-3)^2=3
</me>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Find the equation of the plane that passes through the point
<m>(-2,0,1)</m> and through the line of intersection of <m>2x+3y-z=0,\ x-4y+2z=-5</m>.
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<m>3x-y+z=-5</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Set <m>y=0</m> and then solve <m>2x+3y-z=0,\ x-4y+2z=-5</m>, i.e.
<m>2x-z=0</m>, <m>x+2z=-5</m>, or equvalently
<me>
z=2x,\ x+2z=5x=-5
</me>
The result, <m>(-1,0,-2)</m>, is one point on the plane. Set <m>y=5</m> and then
solve <m>2x+3y-z=0,\ x-4y+2z=-5</m>, i.e. <m>2x+15-z=0</m>, <m>x-20+2z=-5</m>,
or equivalently
<me>
z=2x+15,\ x-20+4x+30=-5
</me>
The result, <m>(-3,5,9)</m>, is another
point on the plane. So three points on the plane are <m>(-2,0,1),
\ (-1,0,-2)</m> and <m>(-3,5,9)</m>.
<m>\llt -2+1\,,\,0-0\,,\, 1+2 \rgt=\llt -1,0,3\rgt</m> and
<m>\llt -2+3\,,\,0-5\,,\, 1-9 \rgt = \llt 1,-5,-8\rgt</m> are two
vectors having both head and tail in the plane.
<md>
<mrow>
\llt -1,0,3\rgt \times  \llt 1,-5,-8\rgt
=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
           \hi &amp; \hj &amp; \hk
</mrow><mrow>
           -1  &amp;  0  &amp;  3
</mrow><mrow>
            1  &amp;  -5 &amp;  -8
  \end{matrix}\right]
=\llt 15 , -5 ,5  \rgt
</mrow>
</md>
is a vector perpendicular to the plane.
<m>\frac{1}{5}\llt 15 , -5 ,5  \rgt=\llt 3,-1,1\rgt</m>
is also a vector perpendicular to the plane. The plane is
<me>
3(x+1) -(y-0) + (z+2)=0\quad\text{or}\quad
3x-y+z=-5
</me>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Find the distance from the point <m>\vp</m> to the plane <m>\vn\cdot
\vx= c</m>.
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<m>|c-\vn\cdot\vp|/|\vn|</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
The vector <m>\vn</m> is perpendicular to the plane
<m>\vn\cdot\vx= c</m>. So the line
<me>
\vx(t)=\vp+t\vn
</me>
passes through <m>\vp</m> and is perpendicular to the plane.
</p>
<sidebyside width="">
<image source="pfigs/distance.svg"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
It crosses the plane at the value of <m>t</m> which obeys
<me>
\vn\cdot\vx(t)= c
\hskip .25 in\text{or}\hskip .25 in
\vn\cdot[\vp+t\vn]= c
</me>
namely
<me>
t=[c-\vn\cdot\vp]/|\vn|^2
</me>
The vector
<me>
\vx(t)-\vp=t\,\vn=\vn\,[c-\vn\cdot\vp]/|\vn|^2
</me>
has head on the plane <m>\vn\cdot\vx= c</m>, tail at <m>\vp</m>, and
is perpendicular to the plane. So the distance is the length of that
vector, which is
<me>
|c-\vn\cdot\vp|/|\vn|
</me>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Describe the set of points equidistant from <m>(1,2,3)</m> and
<m>(5,2,7)</m>.
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
It is the plane <m>x+z=8</m>, which is
the plane through <m>(3,2,5)=\half(1,2,3)+\half(5,2,7)</m> with normal
<m>\llt 1,0,1\rgt=\frac{1}{4}\big(\llt 5,2,7\rgt-\llt 1,2,3\rgt \big)</m>.
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
The distance from the point <m>(x,y,z)</m> to <m>(1,2,3)</m>
is <m>\sqrt{(x-1)^2+(y-2)^2+(z-3)^2}</m> and
the distance from <m>(x,y,z)</m>to <m>(5,2,7)</m> is
<m>\sqrt{(x-5)^2+(y-2)^2+(z-7)^2}</m>. Hence <m>(x,y,z)</m> is equidistant
from <m>(1,2,3)</m> and <m>(5,2,7)</m> if and only if
<md>
<mrow>
&amp; &amp; (x-1)^2+(y-2)^2+(z-3)^2&amp;=(x-5)^2+(y-2)^2+(z-7)^2
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\iff &amp; x^2-2x+1+z^2-6z+9&amp;=x^2-10x+25+z^2-14z+49
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\iff &amp; 8x+8z&amp;=64
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\iff &amp; x+z&amp;=8
</mrow>
</md>
This is the plane through <m>(3,2,5)=\half(1,2,3)+\half(5,2,7)</m>
with normal vector
<m>\llt 1,0,1\rgt=\frac{1}{4}\big(\llt 5,2,7\rgt-\llt 1,2,3\rgt \big)</m>.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
 Describe the set of points equidistant from <m>\va</m> and <m>\vb</m>.
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
It is the plane <m>2(\vb-\va)\cdot\vx=|\vb|^2-|\va|^2</m>,
which is the plane through <m>\half\va+\half\vb</m>
with normal vector  <m>\vb-\va</m>.
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
The distance from the point <m>\vx</m> to <m>\va</m> is
<m>\sqrt{(\vx-\va)\cdot(\vx-\va)}</m> and the distance from <m>\vx</m> to <m>\vb</m> is
<m>\sqrt{(\vx-\vb)\cdot(\vx-\vb)}</m>. Hence <m>\vx</m> is equidistant
from <m>\va</m> and <m>\vb</m> if and only if
<md alignment="alignat">
<mrow>{3}
&amp; &amp; (\vx-\va)\cdot(\vx-\va)&amp;=(\vx-\vb)\cdot(\vx-\vb)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\iff\qquad &amp; |\vx|^2-2\va\cdot\vx+|\va|^2&amp;=|\vx|^2-2\vb\cdot\vx+|\vb|^2
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\iff &amp; 2(\vb-\va)\cdot\vx&amp;=|\vb|^2-|\va|^2
</mrow>
</md>
This is the plane through <m>\half\va+\half\vb</m>
with normal vector  <m>\vb-\va</m>.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M200 2003D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Consider a point <m>P(5,-10,2)</m> and the triangle with vertices
<m>A(0,1,1)</m>, <m>B(1,0,1)</m> and <m>C(1,3,0)</m>.
<ol label="a">
<li>
Compute the area of the triangle <m>ABC</m>.
</li>
<li>
Find the distance from the point <m>P</m> to the plane containing
the triangle.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<ol label="a">
<li><m>\half\sqrt{11}\approx 1.658</m></li>
<li><m>\frac{3}{\sqrt{11}}\approx 0.9045</m></li>
</ol>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
(a) One side of the triangle is
      <m>\overrightarrow{AB}=\llt 1,0,1\rgt - \llt 0,1,1\rgt = \llt 1,-1,0\rgt</m>.
A second side of the triangle is
      <m>\overrightarrow{AC}=\llt 1,3,0\rgt - \llt 0,1,1\rgt = \llt 1,2,-1\rgt</m>.
If the angle between <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{AC}</m>
is <m>\theta</m> and if we take <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> as the base of the triangle,
then the triangle has base length <m>b=|\overrightarrow{AB}|</m>
and height <m>h=|\overrightarrow{AC}|\sin\theta</m> and hence
<me>
\text{area}=\half bh
=\half |\overrightarrow{AB}|\,|\overrightarrow{AC}|\sin\theta
=\half|\overrightarrow{AB}\times\overrightarrow{AC}|
=\half|\llt 1,-1,0\rgt \times \llt 1,2,-1\rgt|
</me>
As
<me>
\llt 1,-1,0\rgt\times\llt 1,2,-1\rgt
=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
           \hi &amp; \hj &amp; \hk \\
            1  &amp;  -1  &amp;  0 \\
            1  &amp;  2   &amp;  -1
  \end{matrix}\right]
=\hi+\hj+3\hk
</me>
we have
<me>
\text{area}=\half|\llt 1,1,3\rgt|=\half\sqrt{11}\approx 1.658
</me>
</p>

<p>(b) A unit vector perpendicular to the plane containing the
triangle is
<me>
\hn=\frac{\overrightarrow{AB}\times\overrightarrow{AC}}
            {|\overrightarrow{AB}\times\overrightarrow{AC}|}
=\frac{\llt 1,1,3\rgt}{\sqrt{11}}
</me>
The distance from <m>P</m> to the plane containing the triangle is
the length of the projection of
<m>\overrightarrow{AP}=\llt 5,-10,2\rgt-\llt 0,1,1\rgt
               =\llt 5,-11,1\rgt</m>
on <m>\hn</m>. If <m>\theta</m> the angle between <m>\overrightarrow{AP}</m>
and <m>\hn</m>, then this is
<me>
\text{distance}= |\overrightarrow{AP}|\,|\cos\theta|
=\big|\overrightarrow{AP}\cdot\hn\big|
=\left|\llt 5,-11,1\rgt\cdot\frac{\llt 1,1,3\rgt}{\sqrt{11}}\right|
=\frac{3}{\sqrt{11}}\approx 0.9045
</me>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M200 2003A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Consider the sphere given by
<me>
(x-1)^2+(y-2)^2+(z+1)^2=2
</me>
Suppose that you are at the point <m>(2,2,0)</m> on <m>S</m>, and you plan to follow
the shortest path on <m>S</m> to <m>(2,1,-1)</m>. Express your initial direction
as a cross product.
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
Any positive constant times
<m>\llt 1,1,-1\rgt\times\llt 1,0,1\rgt
=\llt 1, -2, -1\rgt</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Switch to a new coordinate system with
<me>
X=x-1\qquad Y=y-2\qquad Z=z+1
</me>
In this new coordinate system, the sphere has equation <m>X^2+Y^2+Z^2=2</m>.
So the sphere is centred at <m>(X,Y,Z)=(0,0,0)</m> and has radius <m>\sqrt{2}</m>.
In the new coordinate system, the initial point <m>(x,y,z)=(2,2,0)</m>
has <m>(X,Y,Z)=(1,0,1)</m> and our final point  <m>(x,y,z)=(2,1,-1)</m>
has <m>(X,Y,Z)=(1,-1,0)</m>. Call the initial point <m>P</m> and the final point
<m>Q</m>. The shortest path will follow the great circle from <m>P</m> to <m>Q</m>.
</p>

<sidebyside width="">
  <image source="pfigs/OE03AQB.svg"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
A great circle on a sphere is the intersection of the sphere with a plane
that contains the centre of the sphere. Our strategy for finding the initial
direction will be based on two observations.
<ul>
<li> The shortest path lies on the plane <m>\Pi</m> that contains the origin and the points <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>. Since the shortest path lies on <m>\Pi</m>,
our direction vector must also lie on <m>\Pi</m> and hence must
be perpendicular to the normal vector to <m>\Pi</m>.
</li>
<li>
The shortest path also remains on the sphere, so our initial direction
must also be perpendicular to the normal vector to
the sphere at our initial point <m>P</m>.
</li>
</ul>
As our initial direction is perpendicular to the two normal vectors,
it is parallel to their cross product.
</p>

<p>So our main job is to find normal vectors to the plane <m>\Pi</m> and to the
sphere at <m>P</m>.
<ul>
<li> One way to find a normal vector to <m>\Pi</m> is to guess an equation for
<m>\Pi</m>. As <m>(0,0,0)</m> is on <m>\Pi</m>, <m>(0,0,0)</m> must obey <m>\Pi</m>'s equation.
So <m>\Pi</m>'s equation must be of the form <m>aX+bY+cZ=0</m>. That <m>(X,Y,Z)=(1,0,1)</m>
is on <m>\Pi</m> forces <m>a+c=0</m>.   That <m>(X,Y,Z)=(1,-1,0)</m> is on <m>\Pi</m> forces
<m>a-b=0</m>. So we may take <m>a=1</m>, <m>b=1</m> and <m>c=-1</m>. That is, <m>\Pi</m> is
<m>X+Y-Z=0</m>.  (Check that all three points <m>(0,0,0)</m>, <m>(1,0,1)</m> and
<m>(1,-1,0)</m> do indeed obey <m>X+Y-Z=0</m>.) A normal vector to <m>\Pi</m> is
<m>\llt 1,1,-1\rgt</m>.
</li>
<li><p> A second way to find a normal vector to <m>\Pi</m> is to observe that
both
<ul>
<li>
the vector from <m>(0,0,0)</m> to <m>(1,0,1)</m>, that is <m>\llt 1,0,1\rgt</m>,
lies completely inside <m>\Pi</m> and
</li>
<li>
the vector from <m>(0,0,0)</m> to <m>(1,-1,0)</m>, that is <m>\llt 1,-1,0\rgt</m>,
lies completely inside <m>\Pi</m>.
</li>
</ul>
So the vector
<me>
\llt 1,0,1\rgt\times\llt 1,-1,0\rgt
=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
                     \hi &amp; \hj &amp; \hk \\
                     1   &amp;  0  &amp; 1 \\
                     1   &amp;  -1  &amp; 0
                \end{matrix}\right]
=\hi + \hj -\hk
</me>
is perpendicular to <m>\Pi</m>.</p>
</li>
<li>
The vector from the centre of the sphere to the point <m>P</m> on the sphere
is perpendicular to the sphere at <m>P</m>. So a normal vector to
the sphere at our initial point <m>(X,Y,Z)=(1,0,1)</m> is <m>\llt 1,0,1\rgt</m>.
</li>
</ul>
Since our initial direction
<fn>Note that the change of coordinates
<m>X=x-1</m>, <m>Y=y-2</m>, <m>Z=z+1</m> has absolutely no effect on any velocity or direction
vector. If our position at time <m>t</m> is <m>(x(t),y(t),z(t))</m> in the
original coordinate system, then it is <m>(X(t),Y(t),Z(t))
=(x(t)-1,y(t)-2,z(t)+1)</m> in the new coordinate system. The velocity
vectors in the two coordinate systems <m>\llt x'(t),y'(t),z'(t)\rgt
=\llt X'(t),Y'(t),Z'(t)\rgt</m> are identical.</fn>
</p>

<p>must be perpendicular to both <m>\llt 1,1,-1\rgt</m> and <m>\llt 1,0,1\rgt</m>,
it must be one of  <m>\pm\llt 1,1,-1\rgt\times\llt 1,0,1\rgt</m>.
To get from <m>(1,0,1)</m> to <m>(1,-1,0)</m> by the shortest path, our <m>Z</m>
coordinate should decrease from <m>1</m> to <m>0</m>. So the <m>Z</m> coordinate of
our initial direction should be negative. This is the case for
<me>
\llt 1,1,-1\rgt\times\llt 1,0,1\rgt
